31:48.507 --> 31:51.576 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ended up resulting in a cancer.

31:51.610 --> 31:55.847 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Researchers here
have published
hundreds of papers documenting
the links between

31:55.881 --> 32:01.186 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
radiation and its ill health
effects, primarily
cancer. They have written the
book that is

32:01.219 --> 32:05.757 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the basis for the standards for
acceptable
radiation exposure.

32:05.791 --> 32:11.096 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Among the findings over the
years: Thyroid
cancer and leukemia are the
first to strike.

32:11.129 --> 32:16.835 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Solid cancers come 10 to 30
years later. Young
people are more susceptible to
developing

32:16.868 --> 32:23.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
cancer than adults, and women
are more susceptible
than men. Perhaps the most
important, a single

32:23.475 --> 32:27.179 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
exposure increases cancer risk
for life.

32:27.212 --> 32:34.219 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The bottom line? Of 94,000
survivors studied
over 70 years, about 1,000
additional cases

32:34.252 --> 32:37.722 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of cancer can be attributed to
radiation from
the bombs.

32:37.756 --> 32:39.491 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN BOICE, National Council on
Radiation
Protection and Measurements: So,
the atomic

32:39.524 --> 32:44.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
bomb survivors study, which is a
remarkable
study -- it's the gold standard
in terms of

32:44.229 --> 32:48.300 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
radiation epidemiology -- it has
limitations,
and one of the limitations is,
the dose was

32:48.333 --> 32:50.101 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
given all at once.

32:50.135 --> 32:54.773 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: Radiation
epidemiologist John
Boice is hoping to address that
limitation.

32:54.806 --> 33:01.680 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He is spearheading a study of
workers from
the Manhattan Project, atomic
veterans who

33:01.713 --> 33:07.853 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
witnessed atmospheric bomb
tests, utility
employees at nuclear power
plants, and medical

33:07.886 --> 33:11.356 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
professionals, one million in
all.

33:11.389 --> 33:16.928 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Radiation exposure data captured
by the dosimeters
routinely worn by these workers
over the years

33:16.962 --> 33:20.265 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is compared with their health
history and
cause of death.

33:20.298 --> 33:25.070 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN BOICE: So, when we complete
this study,
that we will be able to say what
the risks

33:25.103 --> 33:31.109 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are from these various levels of
radiation.
Are they the same as Hiroshima
and Nagasaki?

33:31.142 --> 33:32.978 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Are they lower? Are they higher?

33:33.011 --> 33:37.883 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Some studies
suggest our bodies
can fight back and repair damage
caused by

33:37.916 --> 33:45.390 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
low-level, yet chronic, exposure
to radiation.
But no one is sure.

33:45.423 --> 33:51.062 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Biophysicist David Brenner is
also hoping
to fill in some of this
uncharted territory.

33:51.096 --> 33:55.934 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He is director of the Center for
Radiological
Research at Columbia University
Medical Center.

33:55.967 --> 33:58.470 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DAVID BRENNER, Columbia
University Medical
Center: Any level of radiation
can produce

33:58.503 --> 34:01.940 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DNA damage, which ultimately can
produce a
cancer.

34:01.973 --> 34:07.312 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: But when the
doses get very
low, scientists are hard-pressed
to quantify

34:07.345 --> 34:12.617 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the link between radiation and
cancer. There
is just too much cancer out
there already.

34:12.651 --> 34:16.721 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Four in 10 Americans will
eventually battle
the disease anyway.

34:16.755 --> 34:21.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID BRENNER: So how do you
detect a very
small increase in that 40
percent? And if

34:21.593 --> 34:28.199 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there was an increase from 40
percent to 40.1
percent, how would we ever
detect that? And

34:28.233 --> 34:29.601 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that's really our problem.

34:29.634 --> 34:33.238 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: So could there be
a line below
which there is no risk?

34:33.271 --> 34:39.144 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID BRENNER: But what we're
trying to do
is to figure out, what is the
best way to

34:39.177 --> 34:45.550 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
extrapolate the risks that we
know from high
doses to low doses? In order to
do that, we

34:45.583 --> 34:51.389 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
really want to know the
mechanism on how exactly
does radiation produce cancer.

34:51.423 --> 34:56.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Brenner employs a
particle
accelerator to try and find some
answers.

34:56.361 --> 35:00.932 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
In experiments, he aims
high-energy protons
at a single cell.

35:00.966 --> 35:06.071 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID BRENNER: What we want to
do is to be
able to expose a cell to
radiation, but not

35:06.104 --> 35:11.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
expose all the neighbor cells to
radiation,
because that's actually what --
the real-life

35:11.443 --> 35:13.545 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
situation at very, very low
doses.

35:13.578 --> 35:18.316 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: This isn't just
an academic
pursuit. The atomic bomb
survivors study is

35:18.350 --> 35:23.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the basis of risk estimates for
everything
from doses in medical care, to
work rules

35:23.488 --> 35:29.094 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for radiation workers, to
evacuation orders
in the wake of a nuclear power
plant meltdown.

35:29.127 --> 35:34.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But these rules, which can
affect so many
lives in so many devastating
ways, are based

35:34.666 --> 35:42.107 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
solely on educated guesswork. In
January 2015,
the U.S. House passed the
low-dose radiation

35:42.140 --> 35:47.779 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
bill which would provide funds
to begin a
large study. But the bill
stalled in the Senate,

35:47.812 --> 35:53.018 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
frustrating scientists who
believe the nation
that unleashed the nuclear age
is obligated

35:53.051 --> 35:58.890 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to never stop trying to fully
comprehend its
long-term impact.

35:58.923 --> 36:10.802 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Miles O'Brien, the "PBS
NewsHour," Hiroshima,
Japan.

36:10.835 --> 36:21.546 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: In October
2015 an American
AC-130 gunship pummeled the
Doctors Without

36:21.579 --> 36:27.052 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Borders hospital in Kunduz,
Afghanistan, hitting
what the crew believed to be a
Taliban fighting

36:27.085 --> 36:28.820 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
position.

36:28.853 --> 36:32.557 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The plane rained artillery and
other fire
on the facility, killing 42
people, despite

36:32.590 --> 36:38.029 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
frantic calls from the group,
known by its
French acronym, MSF, to stop the
attack.

36:38.063 --> 36:42.867 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Last month, an Army
investigation found there
was no intent by the Americans
to destroy

36:42.901 --> 36:48.640 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the hospital, either by the air
crew or the
American special forces on the
ground who

36:48.673 --> 36:54.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
were calling in for fire. The
probe found
that it was a targeting error
born of confusion

36:54.779 --> 36:57.849 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and miscommunication in the fog
of war.

36:57.882 --> 37:02.520 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Sixteen soldiers were
reprimanded, but no
criminal charges were filed.

37:02.554 --> 37:07.125 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But a new report in "The New
York Times" magazine
by Matthieu Aikins of the Nation
Institute

37:07.158 --> 37:13.631 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
casts doubt on the motivations
of the Afghan
troops who told the Americans
that the hospital

37:13.665 --> 37:15.333 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
was a Taliban stronghold.

37:15.366 --> 37:19.904 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I spoke with Aikins yesterday
and with two
former military attorneys.

37:19.938 --> 37:23.608 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I began by asking the reporter
what may have
motivated this attack.

37:23.641 --> 37:27.145 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MATTHIEU AIKINS, The Nation
Institute: From
the extensive reporting that we
did starting

37:27.178 --> 37:33.184 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from November, as well as
documents that are
buried in the military's
redacted report,

37:33.218 --> 37:38.723 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there's evidence that Afghan
forces may have
provided an exact description
that matched

37:38.756 --> 37:44.596 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the hospital as a target,
meaning that they
intentionally targeted the
hospital, leading

37:44.629 --> 37:48.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
to U.S. forces perhaps
unintentionally striking
the hospital as a result of that
description.

37:48.500 --> 37:52.437 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, why would
Afghan forces
want to strike a hospital?

37:52.470 --> 37:58.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MATTHIEU AIKINS: There's been a
long-simmering
tension between MSF and the
Afghan government,

37:58.743 --> 38:03.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
basically a collision between
two different
world views, MSF, which sees
itself as a neutral

38:03.381 --> 38:08.153 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
humanitarian medical
organization that treats
all sides to a conflict,
regardless of who

38:08.186 --> 38:13.091 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they are, and Afghan forces that
have resented
MSF treating what it views as
its enemy.

38:13.124 --> 38:16.261 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So is there a
widespread
mistrust?

38:16.294 --> 38:21.499 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MATTHIEU AIKINS: What we found,
you know,
when I went to Kunduz, was a
resentment and

38:21.533 --> 38:26.237 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a mistrust of MSF on the part of
the Afghan
forces. They told me they
thought that MSF

38:26.271 --> 38:28.139 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
was supporting the Taliban.

38:28.173 --> 38:32.744 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this, you know, later led to
what turned
out to be false beliefs that MSF
actually

38:32.777 --> 38:35.980 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
had been taken over and there
were Taliban
leadership inside the hospital
at the time

38:36.014 --> 38:37.916 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
it was struck.

38:37.949 --> 38:41.653 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: You have read
the official
military account. You have done
your own reporting.

38:41.686 --> 38:43.521 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Are there discrepancies?

38:43.555 --> 38:47.325 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MATTHIEU AIKINS: I think that
what's unexplained
in the military's report, what
they elide

38:47.358 --> 38:53.264 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the report is that the
AC-130, the gunship
that struck the hospital, after
its navigation

38:53.298 --> 38:59.537 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
systems failed, it then relied
on a visual
description of the target that
was given by

38:59.571 --> 39:01.573 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the special forces ground
commander.

39:01.606 --> 39:06.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that description, as the
military admits,
came from the Afghan forces. The
military

39:06.811 --> 39:09.581 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
basically asked the Afghan
forces what they
wanted to hit.

39:09.614 --> 39:15.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And while the coordinates for
the other target,
you know, the intelligence
headquarters, were

39:15.386 --> 39:20.225 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
passed on, those were correct
coordinates,
they were passed on much earlier
in the evening,

39:20.258 --> 39:22.360 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
around 6:00 p.m., according to
the military,
so that 1:00 a.m., an hour
before the strike,

39:22.393 --> 39:26.164 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
when the military goes back, and
there is
some confusion because of this
failure of

39:26.197 --> 39:29.767 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the navigation system, and they
ask the Afghan
forces, what should we be
hitting here, the

39:29.801 --> 39:36.708 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Afghan forces pass up a
description that distinctly
resembled the MSF hospital and
in no way resembled

39:36.741 --> 39:38.610 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the intelligence headquarters.

39:38.643 --> 39:43.748 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now, according
to the MSF,
they call it -- they describe it
as an uncontrolled

39:43.781 --> 39:47.518 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
operation in a crowded area. Is
there evidence
of that?

39:47.552 --> 39:51.856 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MATTHIEU AIKINS: Yes, I think
this is a very
crowded city. It's Afghanistan's
fifth largest

39:51.890 --> 39:53.691 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
city.

39:53.725 --> 39:58.263 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the fact that they're
blindly striking
essentially a target in a
crowded area raises

39:58.296 --> 40:02.834 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
questions of recklessness and
negligence.
But we actually go further than
that and suggest

40:02.867 --> 40:06.537 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that the Afghan forces may have
intended to
deliberately target the
hospital.

40:06.571 --> 40:10.475 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: You also cite
different
correspondences that members of
the military

40:10.508 --> 40:14.646 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
who were involved in the
operation had with
members of Congress or others.
What was their

40:14.679 --> 40:19.150 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
view on what was happening at
the time, and
did that change after the fact?

40:19.183 --> 40:20.919 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MATTHIEU AIKINS: Well,
absolutely.

40:20.952 --> 40:24.989 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We were provided with an e-mail
from one of
the special forces troopers on
the ground

40:25.023 --> 40:30.561 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who said that, you know, there
were Taliban
inside. They had kidnapped the
doctors, and

40:30.595 --> 40:34.899 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
they had taken it over,
basically suggesting
that the American forces on the
ground had

40:34.932 --> 40:39.137 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
come to believe the false
reports that, you
know, Afghan forces told me they
believed,

40:39.170 --> 40:43.274 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that they provided to American
forces, that
the hospital had been taken over
by the Taliban,

40:43.308 --> 40:45.076 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
which is very troubling.

40:45.109 --> 40:48.046 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, again, it's something that
is not really
contained within the military's
report or

40:48.079 --> 40:49.847 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
addressed by their
investigation.

40:49.881 --> 40:52.984 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: One of the
members of the
MSF told you at the end of your
story about

40:53.017 --> 40:58.423 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the possibility of ever working
in a place
where so many U.N. Security
Council members

40:58.456 --> 41:00.391 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
are involved in active
conflicts.

41:00.425 --> 41:04.095 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MATTHIEU AIKINS: Well, you know,
this has
been a trend around the world.
You have had

41:04.128 --> 41:10.968 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
strikes against MSF facilities
in Syria, in
Yemen, in Sudan, and in other
areas.

41:11.002 --> 41:16.274 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The fact that MSF is being
targeted is an
extremely worrying development
and one that,

41:16.307 --> 41:17.875 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
you know, has been taken to the
Security Council.

41:17.909 --> 41:20.712 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Matthieu
Aikins joining
us from Athens, thanks so much.

41:20.745 --> 41:22.613 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MATTHIEU AIKINS: My pleasure.

41:22.647 --> 41:26.517 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: We take a
deeper look at
the U.S. military's
investigation of the attack

41:26.551 --> 41:30.822 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on the Doctors Without Borders
hospital in
Kunduz and whether the probe
should have gone

41:30.855 --> 41:35.026 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
further with retired Marine
Corps Lieutenant
Colonel Gary Solis. He served as
a company

41:35.059 --> 41:40.465 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
commander in Vietnam and later
as a judge
advocate and military judge
during his 26-year

41:40.498 --> 41:45.036 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
career. He now teaches the law
of armed conflict
at Georgetown University.

41:45.069 --> 41:49.674 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And retired Lieutenant Colonel
Jeffrey Addicott
spent 20 years as judge advocate
in the Army

41:49.707 --> 41:55.146 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and, for part of that time,
served as a senior
legal adviser to special forces.
He is the

41:55.179 --> 41:59.884 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
director of the Center for
Terrorism Law at
St. Mary's University School of
Law in San

41:59.917 --> 42:00.718 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Antonio.

42:00.752 --> 42:02.487 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Gary Solis, I want to start with
you.

42:02.520 --> 42:07.425 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The military admits a series of
cascading
errors that led to this tragedy.
What was

42:07.458 --> 42:09.293 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the most egregious to you?

42:09.327 --> 42:11.596 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LT. COL. GARY SOLIS (RET.), U.S.
Marine Corps:
To me, the most egregious was
that the pilot

42:11.629 --> 42:18.970 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was unsure of his target for an
hour as he
circled overhead, and that he
later fired,

42:19.003 --> 42:24.275 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
despite not -- apparently not
being all that
sure of his target.

42:24.308 --> 42:31.182 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Even two minutes after he
initiated the first
volley, he radioed JTAC on the
ground asking

42:31.215 --> 42:35.520 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for confirmation that he had hit
the target.
He still was unsure that he had
hit the correct

42:35.553 --> 42:39.490 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
target, and, to me, that's the
most egregious
of a series of errors that were
made.

42:39.524 --> 42:41.259 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
